DC-2

Target IP: 192.168.186.194

Scanning



There are only two TCP ports open on the target machine. The scan above shows the vhost name of this target machine is dc-2. I will need to append this to the /etc/hosts file. The higher port is running SSH application.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

After appending the vhost. The webpage above is displayed. It is running WordPress 4.7.10 application.


There is an interesting section called flag. It mentions we cannot used regular password list to bruteforce. Instead, I need to use cewl.


The /index.php contains plenty of words which can be useful for cewl. I generated the possible password list using the command cewl http://dc-2 -d 3 -w passwords.txt. I stored the passwords in a text file, so I can perform bruteforce"


Looks like there are three users that use this website: admin, jerry, and tom.


Using the command wpscan --password-attack xmlrpc -U "jerry,tom" -t 20 -P passwords.txt --url http://dc-2, I obtained the password of both users.

Exploitation & Privilege Escalation


After looking around the WordPress application to exploit, I did not find anything useful.


But since we have the credentials of both users, maybe we can try SSH instead? And this worked with tom:parturient. But the shell is restricted. Running echo $PATH shows /home/tom/usr/bin. Since vi is included there already, it can be used to break out of the rbash. I used the following commands:

  • vi
  • :set shell=/bin/bash
  • :shell
  • export PATH=/bin:/usr/bin:$PATH
  • export SHELL=/bin/bash:$SHELL


And now I can perform enumeration. Since I already have the password of jerry -- maybe it will work?


And it did!


Looks like only root can run the command above. To spawn a root shell, I used the following commands in order

  • sudo -u root git -p help config
  • !/bin/sh


And now I have a root shell!
